{"type":"message","id":"ca73548c","parentId":"ac5d537f","timestamp":"2026-05-28T21:15:27.958Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_00_UXAlneg5KAUrDQUrOPHD5499","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Too many arguments for this command.\nTry: openclaw config schema --help\n---\nOpenClaw does not recognize option \"--path\".\nTry: openclaw config schema --help\nno channels schema"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":8475,"aggregated":"Too many arguments for this command.\nTry: openclaw config schema --help\n---\nOpenClaw does not recognize option \"--path\".\nTry: openclaw config schema --help\nno channels schema","cwd":"/root/.openclaw/workspace-father"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1780002927956}}
{"type":"message","id":"9c9a4cb9","parentId":"ca73548c","timestamp":"2026-05-28T21:15:29.862Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me look at the documentation for binding config.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_00_byuPPPgD5WwuJ8tNcdX58639","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"openclaw config schema --help 2>&1"},"partialArgs":"{\"command\": \"openclaw config schema --help 2>&1\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_01_qbUUXwIW3leE7YNGHDTp4705","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"grep -r \"route\" /usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/ 2>/dev/null | head -20"},"partialArgs":"{\"command\": \"grep -r \\\"route\\\" /usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/ 2>/dev/null | head -20\"}"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"deepseek","model":"deepseek-v4-flash","usage":{"input":67,"output":118,"cacheRead":76800,"cacheWrite":0,"reasoningTokens":10,"totalTokens":76985,"cost":{"input":0.00000938,"output":0.00003304,"cacheRead":0.0021504,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.00219282}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1780002927969,"responseId":"b546627b-d86d-4989-a784-9f0753595d77"}}
{"type":"message","id":"36b7e7df","parentId":"9c9a4cb9","timestamp":"2026-05-28T21:15:33.941Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_00_byuPPPgD5WwuJ8tNcdX58639","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"OpenClaw 2026.5.26 (10ad3aa) — All your chats, one OpenClaw.\n\nUsage: openclaw config schema [options]\n\nPrint the JSON schema for openclaw.json\n\nOptions:\n  -h, --help  Display help for command"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":3777,"aggregated":"OpenClaw 2026.5.26 (10ad3aa) — All your chats, one OpenClaw.\n\nUsage: openclaw config schema [options]\n\nPrint the JSON schema for openclaw.json\n\nOptions:\n  -h, --help  Display help for command","cwd":"/root/.openclaw/workspace-father"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1780002933939}}
{"type":"message","id":"4ad5e7d6","parentId":"36b7e7df","timestamp":"2026-05-28T21:15:33.943Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_01_qbUUXwIW3leE7YNGHDTp4705","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/automation/cron-jobs.md:For isolated jobs, chat delivery is shared. If a chat route is available, the agent can use the `message` tool even when the job uses `--no-deliver`. If the agent sends to the configured/current target, OpenClaw skips the fallback announce. Otherwise `announce`, `webhook`, and `none` only control what the runner does with the final reply after the agent turn.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/automation/cron-jobs.md:When an agent creates an isolated reminder from an active chat, OpenClaw stores the preserved live delivery target for the fallback announce route. Internal session keys may be lowercase; provider delivery targets are not reconstructed from those keys when current chat context is available.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/automation/cron-jobs.md:Implicit announce delivery uses configured channel allowlists to validate and reroute stale targets. DM pairing-store approvals are not fallback automation recipients; set `delivery.to` or configure the channel `allowFrom` entry when a scheduled job should proactively send to a DM.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/automation/cron-jobs.md:      model: \"openrouter/meta-llama/llama-3.3-70b-instruct:free\",\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/automation/cron-jobs.md:# Show one job, including resolved delivery route\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/automation/cron-jobs.md:    - Delivery mode `none` means no runner fallback send is expected. The agent can still send directly with the `message` tool when a chat route is available.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/automation/cron-jobs.md:    - If the agent should message the user itself, check that the job has a usable route (`channel: \"last\"` with a previous chat, or an explicit channel/target).\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/automation/tasks.md:**Direct delivery** - if the task has a channel target (the `requesterOrigin`), the completion message goes straight to that channel (Telegram, Discord, Slack, etc.). Group and channel task completions are instead routed through the requester session so the parent agent can write the visible reply. For subagent completions, OpenClaw also preserves bound thread/topic routing when available and can fill a missing `to` / account from the requester session's stored route (`lastChannel` / `lastTo` / `lastAccountId`) before giving up on direct delivery.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/.i18n/zh-Hans-navigation.json:            \"zh-CN/providers/openrouter\",\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/cli/acp.md:ACP does not pick agents directly. It routes by the Gateway session key.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/cli/voicecall.md:When the Gateway is running, operational commands (`call`, `start`, `continue`, `speak`, `dtmf`, `end`, `status`) are routed to that Gateway's voice-call runtime. If no Gateway is reachable, they fall back to a standalone CLI runtime.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/cli/policy.md:      \"deny\": [\"openrouter\"],\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/cli/mcp.md:Use [`openclaw acp`](/cli/acp) when OpenClaw should host a coding harness session itself and route that runtime through ACP.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/cli/mcp.md:- you already have a local or remote OpenClaw Gateway with routed sessions\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/cli/mcp.md:`openclaw mcp serve` starts a stdio MCP server. The MCP client owns that process. While the client keeps the stdio session open, the bridge connects to a local or remote OpenClaw Gateway over WebSocket and exposes routed channel conversations over MCP.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/cli/mcp.md:The bridge uses existing Gateway session route metadata to expose channel-backed conversations. A conversation appears when OpenClaw already has session state with a known route such as:\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/cli/mcp.md:- list recent routed conversations\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/cli/mcp.md:- send a reply back through the same route\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/cli/mcp.md:    Lists recent session-backed conversations that already have route metadata in Gateway session state.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/cli/mcp.md:    Sends text back through the same route already recorded on the session."}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":353,"aggregated":"/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/automation/cron-jobs.md:For isolated jobs, chat delivery is shared. If a chat route is available, the agent can use the `message` tool even when the job uses `--no-deliver`. If the agent sends to the configured/current target, OpenClaw skips the fallback announce. Otherwise `announce`, `webhook`, and `none` only control what the runner does with the final reply after the agent turn.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/automation/cron-jobs.md:When an agent creates an isolated reminder from an active chat, OpenClaw stores the preserved live delivery target for the fallback announce route. Internal session keys may be lowercase; provider delivery targets are not reconstructed from those keys when current chat context is available.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/automation/cron-jobs.md:Implicit announce delivery uses configured channel allowlists to validate and reroute stale targets. DM pairing-store approvals are not fallback automation recipients; set `delivery.to` or configure the channel `allowFrom` entry when a scheduled job should proactively send to a DM.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/automation/cron-jobs.md:      model: \"openrouter/meta-llama/llama-3.3-70b-instruct:free\",\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/automation/cron-jobs.md:# Show one job, including resolved delivery route\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/automation/cron-jobs.md:    - Delivery mode `none` means no runner fallback send is expected. The agent can still send directly with the `message` tool when a chat route is available.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/automation/cron-jobs.md:    - If the agent should message the user itself, check that the job has a usable route (`channel: \"last\"` with a previous chat, or an explicit channel/target).\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/automation/tasks.md:**Direct delivery** - if the task has a channel target (the `requesterOrigin`), the completion message goes straight to that channel (Telegram, Discord, Slack, etc.). Group and channel task completions are instead routed through the requester session so the parent agent can write the visible reply. For subagent completions, OpenClaw also preserves bound thread/topic routing when available and can fill a missing `to` / account from the requester session's stored route (`lastChannel` / `lastTo` / `lastAccountId`) before giving up on direct delivery.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/.i18n/zh-Hans-navigation.json:            \"zh-CN/providers/openrouter\",\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/cli/acp.md:ACP does not pick agents directly. It routes by the Gateway session key.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/cli/voicecall.md:When the Gateway is running, operational commands (`call`, `start`, `continue`, `speak`, `dtmf`, `end`, `status`) are routed to that Gateway's voice-call runtime. If no Gateway is reachable, they fall back to a standalone CLI runtime.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/cli/policy.md:      \"deny\": [\"openrouter\"],\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/cli/mcp.md:Use [`openclaw acp`](/cli/acp) when OpenClaw should host a coding harness session itself and route that runtime through ACP.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/cli/mcp.md:- you already have a local or remote OpenClaw Gateway with routed sessions\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/cli/mcp.md:`openclaw mcp serve` starts a stdio MCP server. The MCP client owns that process. While the client keeps the stdio session open, the bridge connects to a local or remote OpenClaw Gateway over WebSocket and exposes routed channel conversations over MCP.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/cli/mcp.md:The bridge uses existing Gateway session route metadata to expose channel-backed conversations. A conversation appears when OpenClaw already has session state with a known route such as:\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/cli/mcp.md:- list recent routed conversations\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/cli/mcp.md:- send a reply back through the same route\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/cli/mcp.md:    Lists recent session-backed conversations that already have route metadata in Gateway session state.\n/usr/local/lib/node_modules/openclaw/docs/cli/mcp.md:    Sends text back through the same route already recorded on the session.","cwd":"/root/.openclaw/workspace-father"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1780002933941}}
